oem on Linnaean botany, handwritten in the eighteenth century, and subsequently traces the development of a new genre of women’s writing — the botanical poem with scientific notes.The book is indispensable reading for all scholars of the eighteenth century, especially those interested in Romantic women’s writing, or the relationship between literature and science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBotanical literaturexWomen authorsxHistoryx18th century. 0aBotanical literaturexWomen authorsxHistoryy18th century. 0aBotany in literaturexHistoryx18th century. 0aBotany in literaturexHistoryy18th century. 0aPlants, Sex invEarly works to 1800. 0aPlants, Sex inxEarly works to 1800. 0aWomen botanistsxHistoryx18th century. 0aWomen botanistsxHistoryy18th century. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish women's engagement.  aCarl Linnaeus.  aCollinsonia.  aErasmus Darwin.  aLinnaean Sexual System.  aLinnaean classification.  aMary Wollstonecraft.  abotanical classification.  abotanical literature.  aeighteenth-century Britain.  afemale mind.  afemale modesty.  afloristry.  aplant sexuality.  asexual anxiety.1 aGeorge, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130174423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130174/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013